description: From Middle English *inwork, *inwerk, from Old English inweorc (“indoor work”), equivalent to in- +‎ work. Cognate with Scots inwark, inwork (“domestic work, indoor work”).

entries.meaning: (rare) Indoor work; work done inside the home.
examples: Many respondents saw their earnings as a marginal, even though often essential, contribution to the household budget and one outside the formal constraints of inwork.

description: From in- +‎ work. Compare Dutch inwerken (“to affect, orient”), German einwirken (“to influence, impinge”).

verbs.description: inwork (third-person singular simple present inworks, present participle inworking, simple past and past participle inwrought or inworked)

entries.meaning: (transitive, archaic) To work in or into.
(intransitive, archaic) To work or operate within.
